The Babel fish is small, yellow, leech-like, and probably the oddest
thing in the Universe. It feeds on brainwave energy, absorbing all
unconscious frequencies and excreting a telepathic matrix formed from
the conscious frequencies and nerve signals picked up from the speech
centres of the brain.

The practical upshot of all this is that if you stick one in your ear
you can instantly understand anything said to you in any form of
language. The speech patterns you actually hear decode the
brainwave matrix which has been fed into your mind by your Babel fish.

Some scholars have cited the Babel fish as conclusive proof of the
non-existence of a divine creator, on the grounds that something so
mind-bogglingly useful could not possibly have evolved by chance. This
argument has, naturally, caused a great many more wars than it has
settled.

Filing note: do not attempt to insert more than one Babel fish per ear.
The Guide accepts no responsibility for any resulting confusion,
existential crisis, or minor bleeding.Deep Thought was, at the time of its construction, the second greatest
computer in the Universe of Time and Space, built by a hyper-intelligent
pan-dimensional race of beings to answer the Ultimate Question of Life,
the Universe, and Everything.

It took Deep Thought seven and a half million years to compute and
check the answer, which turned out to be, disappointingly, forty-two.
Deep Thought pointed out, not unreasonably, that the answer seemed
meaningless because the beings who instructed it had never actually
known what the Question was.

Deep Thought then designed a successor computer, of such infinite and
subtle complexity that organic life itself would form part of its
operational matrix, to calculate the Question to the Answer. That
computer was called Earth, and it was, unfortunately, demolished by the
Vogons five minutes before the program completed, to make way for a
hyperspace bypass.Harmless.

That was the entire entry in the first edition of this Guide. Later editors,
under pressure from an in-depth study lasting nearly fifteen years and
conducted by a field researcher who spent most of that time at parties,
expanded the entry to two words:

Mostly harmless.

Earth is a small, insignificant blue-green planet orbiting an
unregarded yellow sun in the unfashionable western spiral arm of the
Galaxy. Despite this, it is home to a species that spends a
considerable amount of its time inventing things it does not need,
worrying about things it cannot change, and building digital wristwatches.

Notable exports: none of any galactic significance.
Notable imports: bad news, mostly regarding forthcoming hyperspace bypasses.
Danger rating: negligible, unless you happen to be standing on it when the
Vogons arrive with the paperwork.The Infinite Improbability Drive is a wonderful new method of crossing
vast interstellar distances in a mere nothingth of a second, without all
that tedious mucking about in hyperspace.

It was discovered by generating a strong Brownian Motion producer (say,
a nice hot cup of tea) and using it to power a Finite Improbability
Generator, which was connected to the atomic vector plotter already
existing in all matter transference beams, then feeding into this the
whole infinite improbability of a vessel's precise position and
non-position in space and time.

The drive works by making a spaceship briefly become every particle in
the universe simultaneously, before reassembling itself in a random
(and often mildly improbable) location. Side effects can include, but
are not limited to: temporary transformation into unlikely objects,
spontaneous knitting, and the sudden appearance of bowls of petunias
and irate sperm whales.

The odds against a working drive being discovered by chance were
calculated at exactly two to the power of infinity to one against, a
figure which a bright young student on Earth then proved was not,
actually, all that big a number.Magrathea is a legendary planet, believed by many to be a myth, whose
entire economy was based on the manufacture of custom-made luxury
planets for the very rich. Business, according to the more paranoid
historians, was so good that the whole of the rest of the galactic
economy eventually collapsed, since nobody could afford to buy their
other, less impressive, imported products any more.

Magrathea then vanished, its location wiped from every star chart,
possibly out of embarrassment, possibly out of very sound commercial
planning. It is said its inhabitants slept for aeons, waiting for the
economy to pick back up, keeping their planet-building factories on
standby just in case.

Visitors are, on the whole, not encouraged, on account of the automated
defence systems, which tend to open with polite recorded messages before
opening fire.The Pan Galactic Gargle Blaster is widely regarded as the best drink in
existence. Its effect has been described as like having your brains
smashed out by a slice of lemon wrapped round a large gold brick.

The Guide lists the recipe as follows: take the juice from one bottle of
that Ol' Janx Spirit, pour it into a measure of water from the seas of
Santraginus V, allow three cubes of Arcturan Mega-gin to melt into it,
add four litres of Fallian marsh gas, over the back of a silver spoon
float a measure of Qualactin Hypermint extract, drop in the tooth of an
Algolian Suntiger, allow to fizzle, add the juice of one whole
Zamphuor, and finally, decorate with an olive.

Bar staff across the galaxy are advised that the drink is somewhat
expensive to make properly, on account of the difficulty involved in
obtaining fresh Zamphuor.

Recommended consumption: no more than one, ever, unless you happen to be
a large mauve creature with more than four arms.The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy is an indispensable companion to
all those who are keen to see the marvels of the Universe for less than
thirty Altairian dollars a day.

It is a wholly remarkable book. It has been compiled and recompiled many
times over many years by many hands, of widely differing wisdom and
temperament, and though it falls short of the definitive perfection
that is required of it, it remains one of the more remarkable pieces
of freelance journalism to have come out of the Ursa Minor
publishing corporation.

Though it has many omissions, and contains much that is apocryphal, or
at least wildly inaccurate, it scores over the more pedestrian
Encyclopedia Galactica in two important respects. First, it is
slightly cheaper. Second, it has the words DON'T PANIC inscribed in
large friendly letters on its cover.

This offline edition, adapted for handheld data terminals, contains no
guarantee of accuracy whatsoever, and the editors accept no
responsibility for consequences arising from its use, misuse, or being
dropped in a swimming pool.A towel, the Guide notes, is about the most massively useful thing an
interstellar hitchhiker can carry, and this for quite a number of
reasons.

You can wrap it around you for warmth as you bound across the cold
moons of Jaglan Beta. You can lie on it on the brilliant marble-sanded
beaches of Santraginus V, inhaling the heady sea vapours. You can sleep
under it beneath the stars, which shine so redly on the desert world of
Kakrafoon. You can use it to sail a mini raft down the slow heavy river
Moth. You can wet it for use in hand-to-hand combat. You can wrap it
round your head to avoid the gaze of the Ravenous Bugblatter Beast of
Traal (a mindboggingly stupid animal which assumes that if you can't
see it, it can't see you). You can even, in extremities, use it to flag
down a passing spacecraft, or wave it in the air in mock, or genuine,
distress.

More importantly, a towel has immense psychological value. Any
non-hitchhiker who sees a hitchhiker in possession of a towel will
automatically assume that they are also in possession of a toothbrush,
face flannel, soap, tin of biscuits, flask, compass, map, ball of
string, gnat spray, wet-weather gear, space suit, and so on. Furthermore
the non-hitchhiker will then automatically assume that the hitchhiker
is also carrying a mind-bogglingly capable and resourceful individual
who is clearly not to be messed with.

Hence, a hitchhiker with a towel is a person to be reckoned with.Vogons are one of the most unpleasant races in the galaxy. Not actually
evil, but bad-tempered, bureaucratic, officious, and callous. They
wouldn't lift a finger to save their own grandmothers from a Ravenous
Bugblatter Beast of Traal without express written approval from
Grandmother Disposal, in triplicate, lodged, invoiced, and quintuplicated
with a duty stamp.

When the Vogons first crawled out of the sluggish primeval seas of
Vogsphere, it was as if the forces of evolution had simply given up on
them there and then, turned aside in disgust, and written them off as an
ugly and unfortunate mistake. They never evolved again; they should
never have survived. The fact that they did is a kind of tribute to the
thick-witted, slug-brained stubbornness of these creatures.

Vogon poetry is, of course, the third worst in the universe. On no
account should you allow a Vogon to read poetry at you. The second worst
is that of the Azgoths of Kria. The very worst poetry perished, along
with its creator, when the Guide's offices on Earth were sadly
destroyed, along with the rest of the planet, to make way for a
hyperspace bypass.

When the Vogons discovered the principles of interstellar travel, within
a few short Vog years every last Vogon had migrated to the Megabrantis
cluster, the political hub of the galaxy, and now forms the immensely
powerful backbone of the Galactic Civil Service. Bribing a Vogon is
utterly impossible, on account of their total lack of imagination
regarding what to do with a bribe.